# Business rules — [APP_NAME]

Invariants of this project's domain. Rules that hold regardless of UI, code
language, or storage technology. Violating one of these is a **business
bug**, not just a code bug.

This file is read by `rsct_get_knowledge(category="business-rules")` and by
`rsct_check_premise` before any spec is approved. Spec phase MUST refuse
options that violate a captured rule unless explicit `override_reason` is
given (which itself triggers an anti-decision capture).

---

## When to capture an entry here

Capture a rule when **any** of the following is true:

- A bug fix revealed that an implicit assumption was being violated. Capture
the rule before closing the bug.
- A stakeholder stated a constraint in a meeting/Slack/email
("never...", "always...", "only when...").
- A regulation imposes the rule (LGPD article, fiscal code, payment-network
acceptance, ISO requirement).
- A founder/CTO/architect made an explicit decision that constrains future
work ("we will never store X in plaintext").
- A reasoning step in a plan keeps referencing an unwritten assumption.
Write it down.

## When NOT to capture here

- Technology constraints ("we use PostgreSQL", "we use Redis for cache") →
`architecture.md` or `vendor-relationships.md`.
- Process rules ("PRs need 2 reviewers") → `workflow-rituals.md`.
- One-off edge cases ("if user is born on Feb 29") → `domain-edge-cases.md`.
- Generic best practices ("validate user input") → those are baseline, not
project-specific.

A good test: if a competitor in the same industry would likely follow the
same rule (LGPD compliance, double-entry bookkeeping, payment authorization
before capture) → it belongs here. If only this team would phrase it that
way → maybe `domain-edge-cases.md` instead.

